%U A396766 264,271,272,273,282,289,299,300,307,318,326,335,336,343,344,345,354,361,362,371,372,379,397
%N A396766 Numbers whose number of distinct prime factors equals their digital root.
%C A396766 Since the digital root of n lies in {1..9}, every term has between 1 and 9 distinct prime factors. The sequence is infinite: by Dirichlet's theorem there are infinitely many primes p == 1 (mod 9), and each such prime has exactly one distinct prime factor and digital root 1, hence belongs to the sequence.
%C A396766 For each d from 1 to 9, there are infinitely many terms k with A001221(k) = A010888(k) = d. - _Robert Israel_, Jul 08 2026
%F A396766 { k : A001221(k) = A010888(k) }.
%e A396766 56 = 2^3 * 7 has 2 distinct prime factors {2, 7}; digital root of 56 is 5+6 = 11, then 1+1 = 2; since 2 = 2, 56 is a term.
%e A396766 120 = 2^3 * 3 * 5 has 3 distinct prime factors; digital root is 1+2+0 = 3; since 3 = 3, 120 is a term.
%p A396766 q:= x-> is(((x-1) mod 9)+1=nops(ifactors(x)[2])):
%p A396766 select(q, [$2..397])[];  # _Alois P. Heinz_, Jul 07 2026
%t A396766 Select[Range[400], PrimeNu[#] == (Mod[# - 1, 9] + 1) &]
%o A396766 (PARI) select(n->omega(n)==(n-1)%9+1, [1..400])
%o A396766 (Python) from sympy import primefactors
%o A396766 print([n for n in range(1, 400) if len(primefactors(n)) == 1+(n-1)%9])
%Y A396766 Cf. A001221, A010888, A061237 (subsequence).
